&lt;h1&gt;
&lt;span class="subject"&gt;&lt;a href="/search?l=blink-dev@chromium.org&amp;q=subject:%22Re%5C%3A+%5C%5BEXTERNAL%5C%5D+Re%5C%3A+%5C%5Bblink%5C-dev%5C%5D+Intent+to+ship%5C%3A+Cache+sharing+for+extremely%5C-pervasive+resources%22&amp;o=newest" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;span itemprop="name"&gt;Re: [EXTERNAL] Re: [blink-dev] Intent to ship: Cache sharing for extremely-pervasive resources&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p class="darkgray font13"&gt;
&lt;span class="sender pipe"&gt;&lt;a href="/search?l=blink-dev@chromium.org&amp;q=from:%22Alex+Russell%22" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"&gt;&lt;span itemprop="name"&gt;Alex Russell&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span class="date"&gt;&lt;a href="/search?l=blink-dev@chromium.org&amp;q=date:20251202" rel="nofollow"&gt;Tue, 02 Dec 2025 13:24:36 -0800&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div itemprop="articleBody" class="msgBody"&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;We've been meeting the web where it is for 15 years, and it has only 
created an unsustainable ecosystem of JS excesses. Continuous improvement 
in V8 and DOM and networking, e.g., have not yeilded a faster-feeling web, 
even on devices that get increasingly faster. This is what I'm talking 
about with induced demand: when we lower the cost of excess (rather than 
pushing back on it), the free-riders feel no need to change. Today, that 
very much includes most of the employers of the API OWNERS, and it seems 
disingenuous of us to rubber-stamp those excesses when we have proven well 
beyond any reasonable satisfaction that reeling out more rope doesn't lead 
to sustainable user experience improvements.&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;pre&gt;

The more aggression version of what I'm describing might even be to slow 
down or degrade performance of these scripts relative to their size, 
multiplied by their prevalence. That is, having gathered the data about 
what's popular, shouldn't we be raising the cost of this sort of parasitic 
drag on user CPU/battery/bandwidth/memory, rather than subsidising it? I'd 
be supportive of Edge pulling that lever if we could coordinate on it with 
y'all.

Best,

Alex

On Tuesday, December 2, 2025 at 1:11:38 PM UTC-8 Patrick Meenan wrote:

&gt; The push-back is largely the same (and likely just as ineffective). Most 
&gt; of the resources in the candidate list are updated on a fairly regular 
&gt; cadence so even with cache sharing they are still going to be downloaded 
&gt; quite frequently even for the same users. This also only helps with the 
&gt; download portion, not parse and compile which are as bad, if not worse, 
&gt; particularly on the low-end devices (and even with dictionaries, you still 
&gt; need to parse and compile ALL of the code). There has been ~5 years of 
&gt; &quot;push back&quot; with a fully partitioned cache that had effectively zero impact.
&gt;
&gt; Features, functionality, developer ergonomics, etc, usually take a higher 
&gt; priority than amount of code (not always, but I've been watching the HTTP 
&gt; Archive graphs for WAY too long).
&gt;
&gt; The magnitude of the improvement would likely be highest on slower 
&gt; networks (not necessarily low-end devices except for available storage) and 
&gt; network performance for devices will vary wildly over a given month which 
&gt; would make it a lot more complicated and less useful unless it was sticky 
&gt; (and then it makes the privacy side of things more complicated if it leaks 
&gt; if this user is always on a fast network or not). 
&gt;
&gt; As we've seen with most performance work, even non-visible improvements 
&gt; lead to behavior changes. Consuming more pages, interacting more, etc, 
&gt; particularly in the aggregate.
&gt;
&gt; At this point I'm trying to meet the web where it is and see where we can 
&gt; improve things where the web decided to go.
&gt;
&gt; On Tue, Dec 2, 2025 at 3:52 PM Alex Russell &lt;&lt;a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection" class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="a3d0cfcac4cbd7cfda8d8d8de3c0cbd1cccecad6ce8dccd1c4"&gt;[email&#160;protected]&lt;/a&gt;&gt; 
&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt;&gt; I've been thinking a *lot * about this Intent, and I would feel much 
&gt;&gt; better about it if we were targeting the effects towards users that can 
&gt;&gt; benefit, rather than subsidising the excesses of JS libraries that have 
&gt;&gt; grown without push-back. The YT player, e.g., is egregiously sized, and it 
&gt;&gt; make me queasy to think that we're going to create even more induced demand.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; I'd support a policy, e.g., that made this feature more likely to trigger 
&gt;&gt; the lower-spec'd the device and/or network the user is on.
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Is that something you'd consider supporting, Pat?
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt; Best,
&gt;&gt;
