&lt;div class="msgHead"&gt; &lt;h1&gt; &lt;span class="subject"&gt;&lt;a href="/search?l=blink-dev@chromium.org&amp;q=subject:%22Re%5C%3A+%5C%5BEXTERNAL%5C%5D+Re%5C%3A+%5C%5Bblink%5C-dev%5C%5D+Intent+to+ship%5C%3A+Cache+sharing+for+extremely%5C-pervasive+resources%22&amp;o=newest" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;span itemprop="name"&gt;Re: [EXTERNAL] Re: [blink-dev] Intent to ship: Cache sharing for extremely-pervasive resources&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/h1&gt; &lt;p class="darkgray font13"&gt; &lt;span class="sender pipe"&gt;&lt;a href="/search?l=blink-dev@chromium.org&amp;q=from:%22Alex+Russell%22" rel="nofollow"&gt;&lt;span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"&gt;&lt;span itemprop="name"&gt;Alex Russell&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class="date"&gt;&lt;a href="/search?l=blink-dev@chromium.org&amp;q=date:20251202" rel="nofollow"&gt;Tue, 02 Dec 2025 14:37:15 -0800&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div itemprop="articleBody" class="msgBody"&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;You're right that the problem isn't unique to the web, and I'm suggesting that we learn the lessons of other domains, rather than plowing onward to more induced demand; we have a valuable resource in your research. I'm asking how we might redirect it to change the behaviour of the parties that are degrading the ecosystem to the extent that the band-aid proposed here became necessary at all:&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;pre&gt;
&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Induced_demand"&gt;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Induced_demand&lt;/a&gt;
We (browsers) have power to change developer behaviour; MOAR TLS and CWV proved that. So why should we not lean into that insight here too?
Best,
Alex
On Tuesday, December 2, 2025 at 1:52:02 PM UTC-8 Patrick Meenan wrote:
&gt; Or, the optimist in me sees it as enabling richer web experiences without &gt; getting much slower. It's no different from the situation with desktop &gt; software and Andy and Bill's law &gt; &lt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andy_and_Bill%27s_law"&gt;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andy_and_Bill%27s_law&lt;/a&gt;&gt; (what Andy giveth, &gt; Bill taketh away). &gt; &gt; I'm sure there's some debate over if the web experiences are ACTUALLY &gt; richer, if it is enabling lazier (or faster) development cycles or &gt; something else, but the problem isn't necessarily unique to the web and I'm &gt; not sure that purposefully making it worse would change things for the &gt; better. &gt; &gt; On Tue, Dec 2, 2025 at 4:24 PM Alex Russell &lt;&lt;a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection" class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="c7b4abaea0afb3abbee9e9e987a4afb5a8aaaeb2aae9a8b5a0"&gt;[email&#160;protected]&lt;/a&gt;&gt; &gt; wrote: &gt; &gt;&gt; We've been meeting the web where it is for 15 years, and it has only &gt;&gt; created an unsustainable ecosystem of JS excesses. Continuous improvement &gt;&gt; in V8 and DOM and networking, e.g., have not yeilded a faster-feeling web, &gt;&gt; even on devices that get increasingly faster. This is what I'm talking &gt;&gt; about with induced demand: when we lower the cost of excess (rather than &gt;&gt; pushing back on it), the free-riders feel no need to change. Today, that &gt;&gt; very much includes most of the employers of the API OWNERS, and it seems &gt;&gt; disingenuous of us to rubber-stamp those excesses when we have proven well &gt;&gt; beyond any reasonable satisfaction that reeling out more rope doesn't lead &gt;&gt; to sustainable user experience improvements. &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; The more aggression version of what I'm describing might even be to slow &gt;&gt; down or degrade performance of these scripts relative to their size, &gt;&gt; multiplied by their prevalence. That is, having gathered the data about &gt;&gt; what's popular, shouldn't we be raising the cost of this sort of parasitic &gt;&gt; drag on user CPU/battery/bandwidth/memory, rather than subsidising it? I'd &gt;&gt; be supportive of Edge pulling that lever if we could coordinate on it with &gt;&gt; y'all. &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Best, &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; Alex &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt; On Tuesday, December 2, 2025 at 1:11:38 PM UTC-8 Patrick Meenan wrote: &gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; The push-back is largely the same (and likely just as ineffective). Most &gt;&gt;&gt; of the resources in the candidate list are updated on a fairly regular &gt;&gt;&gt; cadence so even with cache sharing they are still going to be downloaded &gt;&gt;&gt; quite frequently even for the same users. This also only helps with the &gt;&gt;&gt; download portion, not parse and compile which are as bad, if not worse, &gt;&gt;&gt; particularly on the low-end devices (and even with dictionaries, you still &gt;&gt;&gt; need to parse and compile ALL of the code). There has been ~5 years of &gt;&gt;&gt; &quot;push back&quot; with a fully partitioned cache that had effectively zero impact. &gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; Features, functionality, developer ergonomics, etc, usually take a &gt;&gt;&gt; higher priority than amount of code (not always, but I've been watching the &gt;&gt;&gt; HTTP Archive graphs for WAY too long). &gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; The magnitude of the improvement would likely be highest on slower &gt;&gt;&gt; networks (not necessarily low-end devices except for available storage) and &gt;&gt;&gt; network performance for devices will vary wildly over a given month which &gt;&gt;&gt; would make it a lot more complicated and less useful unless it was sticky &gt;&gt;&gt; (and then it makes the privacy side of things more complicated if it leaks &gt;&gt;&gt; if this user is always on a fast network or not). &gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; As we've seen with most performance work, even non-visible improvements &gt;&gt;&gt; lead to behavior changes. Consuming more pages, interacting more, etc, &gt;&gt;&gt; particularly in the aggregate. &gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; At this point I'm trying to meet the web where it is and see where we &gt;&gt;&gt; can improve things where the web decided to go. &gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; On Tue, Dec 2, 2025 at 3:52 PM Alex Russell &lt;&lt;a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection" class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="ed9e81848a85998194c3c3c3ad8e859f8280849880c3829f8a"&gt;[email&#160;protected]&lt;/a&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt; wrote: &gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; I've been thinking a *lot * about this Intent, and I would feel much &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; better about it if we were targeting the effects towards users that can &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; benefit, rather than subsidising the excesses of JS libraries that have &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; grown without push-back. The YT player, e.g., is egregiously sized, and it &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; make me queasy to think that we're going to create even more induced &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; demand. &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; I'd support a policy, e.g., that made this feature more likely to &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; trigger the lower-spec'd the device and/or network the user is on. &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Is that something you'd consider supporting, Pat? &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Best, &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Alex &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; On Thursday, November 27, 2025 at 9:15:26 AM UTC-8 Yoav Weiss wrote: &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; LGTM1 &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; This is an important optimization that will take a small step at &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; evening out the playing field for smaller sites (that use 3Ps and &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; distributed platforms) compared to large, centralized ones with many &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; repeat &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; visitors. It will become even more important once it's integrated with &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Compression Dictionaries, as it would significantly increase cache &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; reusability ev